In article <1992Apr1.182446.21988@linus.mitre.org>
bs@gauss.mitre.org (Robert D. Silverman) writes:

>The theorem [any prime factor of 2^p-1 is congruent 1 or -1 mod 8]
>works because 2 is a primitive root. Any prime that has 2 as a
>primitive root must be congruent to 1 or -1 mod 8. Here, we have 2p+1 = 8n+7.

Um, for "primitive root" read "quadratic residue"; 2 is not a
primitve residue of any factor of 2^p-1 for any odd prime p,
nor can 2 be a primitive root of any prime congruent to 1 or -1
mod 8 (quadratic reciprocity).

--Noam D. Elkies (elkies@zariski.harvard.edu)
  Department of Mathematics, Harvard University
